[To quote my colleague Larry Lutwick: "_Francisella tularensis_, the bacterium that causes tularemia, is considered a category-A bioterrorism agent. Cases associated with the skinning of rabbits usually involve glandular (lymph node) or ulceroglandular (skin and lymph node) infection. Large outbreaks, especially in eastern Europe or Asia, can be associated with water exposure.

Pneumonic tularemia can cause a severe and fatal pneumonia when the organism is spread by aerosol, as might occur in a biological attack. However, pneumonic tularemia also occurs without the involvement of bioterrorism, as demonstrated by posts below in New York City as well as outbreaks on Martha's Vineyard, Massachusetts. Unlike pneumonic plague, pneumonic tularemia does not spread from person to person."

It's that time of year again. While the Arizona report has this disease correctly concentrated in the western and south central states it occurs across the northern tier and along the Atlantic coast states though in smaller numbers. To get an idea of this latter distribution just do a posting recall on "tularemia AND usa". But even in the high incidence areas all we usually see is just the occasional and sporadic dead rabbit. Then suddenly there will be a summer when one suddenly has 10 or more square miles of dead jack rabbits. What triggers it from being a background to a foreground situation is obscure. Over the years the Texas veterinary public health surveillance teams have been running tick safaris. Their collection of _F. tularensis_ strains will vary from the lethal to the essentially apathogenic. The epidemiology and ecology of this disease awaits clarification. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1FWX.]
